<h1>Unit 4: Transoceanic Interconnections</h1>
<p class="subtitle">c. 1450 – c. 1750 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <span class="weighting-badge">Exam Weight: 12–15%</span></p>
<!-- OVERVIEW -->
<div class="overview-box">
<h3 style="margin-top:0;">⛵ Unit Overview</h3>
<p>
Between 1450 and 1750, Europeans used new shipbuilding and navigation technologies to cross the
Atlantic and round Africa. The result was a truly <strong>global</strong> economy for the first time
in history. Portuguese, Spanish, Dutch, English, and French empires stitched together the Americas,
Africa, Europe, and Asia through maritime trade; the <strong>Columbian Exchange</strong> moved crops,
diseases, and people across oceans at catastrophic and transformative scale; and a new
<strong>Atlantic economy</strong> — built on silver, sugar, and enslaved African labor — reshaped
every region it touched.
</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:0;">
<strong>Big question:</strong> How did transoceanic connections between 1450 and 1750 integrate world
economies, transform societies, and produce resistance?
</p>
</div>
<!-- TIMELINE -->
<h2>🗓️ Unit 4 Timeline</h2>
<div class="timeline">
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">c. 1415–1460:</span> Prince Henry the Navigator sponsors Portuguese exploration down the West African coast.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1453:</span> Fall of Constantinople motivates Europeans to seek new trade routes bypassing Ottoman-controlled Mediterranean.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1488:</span> <strong>Bartolomeu Dias</strong> rounds the Cape of Good Hope.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1492:</span> <strong>Columbus</strong> reaches the Caribbean; same year, the Reconquista ends in Spain.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1494:</span> <strong>Treaty of Tordesillas</strong> divides the non-European world between Spain and Portugal.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1498:</span> <strong>Vasco da Gama</strong> reaches Calicut, India, opening direct sea trade between Europe and Asia.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1519–1521:</span> <strong>Cortés</strong> conquers the Aztec Empire; Magellan's expedition begins circumnavigation (completed 1522).</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1532–1533:</span> <strong>Pizarro</strong> conquers the Inca Empire.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1545:</span> Silver strike at <strong>Potosí</strong> (Bolivia) creates the richest mine in the world.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1565:</span> Spanish establish the <strong>Manila Galleon</strong> trade linking Acapulco to the Philippines.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1600 / 1602:</span> British East India Company (1600) and Dutch <strong>VOC</strong> (1602) founded as joint-stock companies.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1607 / 1608:</span> First permanent English colony at Jamestown (1607); French at Quebec (1608).</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1620:</span> Plymouth Colony founded; Mayflower Compact signed.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1680:</span> <strong>Pueblo Revolt</strong> temporarily expels Spanish from New Mexico.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1688:</span> English <strong>Glorious Revolution</strong> strengthens Parliament and limits royal power.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1713:</span> <strong>Treaty of Utrecht</strong> gives Britain the <em>asiento</em> (monopoly on slave trade to Spanish America).</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1739:</span> <strong>Stono Rebellion</strong> — one of the largest slave uprisings in colonial North America.</div>
<div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">c. 1750:</span> Atlantic economy at full scale; European maritime powers dominate global shipping.</div>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.1 -->
<h2>Topic 4.1 — Technological Innovations from 1450 to 1750</h2>
<div class="region-card region-tech">
<h3>🧭 Ships, Tools, and Knowledge</h3>
<p>
European maritime expansion depended on a cluster of technologies — many of them <em>borrowed</em>
from the Islamic world, China, and the Mediterranean. Most were not new inventions but improvements
and combinations that made long-distance ocean travel practical.
</p>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Nao_Victoria.jpg?width=800" alt="Replica of Magellan's ship Victoria" />
<figcaption>Replica of the <em>Victoria</em>, the only ship in Magellan's fleet to complete the first circumnavigation (1519–1522). Carracks and galleons like this combined square and lateen rigs, a stern rudder, and enough cargo space for long voyages.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Ships</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Caravel</strong> (Portuguese, 15th c.): Small, maneuverable ship with lateen sails; ideal for exploration along coastlines.</li>
<li><strong>Carrack (nau):</strong> Larger 3–4 masted ship combining square sails for speed and lateen sails for handling — capable of crossing open ocean and carrying heavy cargo.</li>
<li><strong>Galleon</strong> (16th c.): Armed, large-bellied ship used for Spanish treasure fleets and Manila Galleons.</li>
<li><strong>Fluyt</strong> (Dutch, late 16th c.): Cheap, efficient cargo ship with a small crew — a key reason the Dutch dominated carrying trade.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Navigation Tools</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Magnetic compass</strong> — Chinese origin; essential for directional navigation out of sight of land.</li>
<li><strong>Astrolabe &amp; quadrant</strong> — Islamic-world refinements; measured the altitude of stars to determine latitude.</li>
<li><strong>Stern-post rudder</strong> — Chinese innovation that gave larger ships reliable steering.</li>
<li><strong>Portolan charts</strong> and, later, more accurate world maps — improved knowledge of winds and currents.</li>
<li><strong>Lateen sail</strong> — triangular sail (Arab origin) that allowed sailing into the wind.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Cartographic &amp; Conceptual Shifts</h4>
<ul>
<li>Ptolemy's geography, reintroduced through Islamic copies, gave Europeans a new framework for mapping the world.</li>
<li>Systematic knowledge of the Atlantic's <strong>volta do mar</strong> (the wind system in the North Atlantic used for return voyages to Europe) was a Portuguese specialty.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Gunpowder at Sea</h4>
<ul>
<li>Shipborne cannon — pioneered by the Portuguese in the Indian Ocean — gave small European fleets overwhelming advantages over merchants who were not used to armed trading.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.2 -->
<h2>Topic 4.2 — Exploration: Causes and Events</h2>
<div class="region-card region-explore">
<h3>🌍 Why Europe — and Why Then?</h3>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Vasco_da_Gama_-_1838.png?width=500" alt="Portrait of Vasco da Gama" />
<figcaption>Vasco da Gama, whose 1498 voyage to Calicut opened the first direct European sea route to South Asia.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Why Exploration Started in Europe</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Demand for Asian goods:</strong> Spices, silk, and porcelain had reached Europe through Venetian and Ottoman middlemen, who charged steep markups. European monarchs wanted to go directly to the source.</li>
<li><strong>Fall of Constantinople (1453):</strong> Reinforced the feeling that land routes were controlled by Muslim rivals.</li>
<li><strong>Renaissance curiosity &amp; Christian missionary zeal:</strong> Summed up as "God, Gold, and Glory" — religious mission, wealth, and royal prestige.</li>
<li><strong>State competition:</strong> Portugal, Spain, England, France, and the Dutch Republic competed to claim trade and territory.</li>
<li><strong>Technology and capital:</strong> Ships, guns, and investment instruments made voyages feasible.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Iberian Voyages</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Prince Henry "the Navigator" (d. 1460):</strong> Funded a school of navigation at Sagres and Portuguese expeditions along the West African coast, ultimately reaching the Gold Coast and founding Elmina (1482).</li>
<li><strong>Bartolomeu Dias (1488):</strong> Rounded the Cape of Good Hope.</li>
<li><strong>Christopher Columbus (1492):</strong> Backed by Ferdinand and Isabella of Spain, sailed west in hopes of reaching Asia; made landfall in the Bahamas.</li>
<li><strong>Vasco da Gama (1498):</strong> Sailed around Africa to India, opening the all-sea route to Asia.</li>
<li><strong>Ferdinand Magellan (1519–1522):</strong> Spanish expedition completed the first circumnavigation of the globe.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Cristobal_Colon.jpg?width=400" alt="Portrait of Columbus" />
<figcaption>Christopher Columbus, whose 1492 Atlantic crossing for Ferdinand and Isabella of Spain opened contact between Europe and the Americas.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Conquest of the Americas</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Treaty of Tordesillas (1494):</strong> Papally-mediated split of the non-European world between Spain and Portugal — one reason Portuguese Brazil is Portuguese-speaking.</li>
<li><strong>Hernán Cortés (1519–1521):</strong> Conquered the Aztec Empire with ~500 men, gunpowder weapons, horses, Tlaxcalan and other Native allies resentful of Aztec rule, and — crucially — smallpox.</li>
<li><strong>Francisco Pizarro (1532–1533):</strong> Conquered the Inca Empire after capturing and executing Atahualpa during a civil war between him and his brother Huáscar.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Cort%C3%A9s_y_la_Malinche.jpg?width=600" alt="Cortés and La Malinche" />
<figcaption>Hernán Cortés and <strong>La Malinche</strong> (Doña Marina), the Nahua translator and advisor whose role was crucial in the Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Northern European Explorers</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>John Cabot</strong> (English, 1497): Claimed Newfoundland.</li>
<li><strong>Jacques Cartier</strong> (French, 1534): Explored the St. Lawrence River.</li>
<li><strong>Henry Hudson</strong> (Dutch/English, early 1600s): Sought a Northwest Passage; explored the Hudson River and Bay.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.3 -->
<h2>Topic 4.3 — The Columbian Exchange</h2>
<div class="region-card region-columbian">
<h3>🌽 The Columbian Exchange</h3>
<p>
Named by historian Alfred Crosby, the <strong>Columbian Exchange</strong> is the vast two-way
transfer of plants, animals, diseases, ideas, and people between the Americas ("New World") and
Afro-Eurasia ("Old World") after 1492. It reshaped populations, diets, and ecologies everywhere.
</p>
<h4>From the Americas to Afro-Eurasia</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Crops:</strong> Potatoes, maize (corn), tomatoes, cassava/manioc, cacao, tobacco, chili peppers, vanilla, pineapples.</li>
<li><strong>Effects:</strong> The potato and maize caused major population booms in Ireland, China, and Sub-Saharan Africa; cassava became a staple in Central Africa; tomatoes became essential in Italian cooking; chili peppers transformed cuisines from India to Korea.</li>
</ul>
<h4>From Afro-Eurasia to the Americas</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Crops:</strong> Wheat, rice, sugar, bananas, grapes, coffee, citrus.</li>
<li><strong>Animals:</strong> Horses (transformed Plains Indian societies), cattle, pigs, sheep, goats, chickens.</li>
<li><strong>Livestock</strong> reshaped Native land use and, on many islands, turned rainforest into pasture.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Disease</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Smallpox, measles, influenza, typhus, mumps</strong> devastated Native American populations with no prior immunity. Estimated mortality: 75–90% of pre-contact Indigenous populations in the first 150 years.</li>
<li><strong>Syphilis</strong> may have spread the other direction, from the Americas to Eurasia.</li>
</ul>
<h4>People &amp; Labor</h4>
<ul>
<li>Millions of Europeans migrated to the Americas; an estimated 12.5 million Africans were forcibly transported across the Atlantic between 1500 and 1866.</li>
<li>Native societies were decimated by disease and labor demands; Africa lost population and stable states as slave raiding intensified.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Environmental Effects</h4>
<ul>
<li>Deforestation for sugar, tobacco, and silver mining (especially at Potosí, where mercury amalgamation poisoned landscapes and workers).</li>
<li>"Ghost acres" in Europe and Asia fed by calories grown in American soil.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.4 -->
<h2>Topic 4.4 — Maritime Empires Established</h2>
<div class="region-card region-maritime">
<h3>🗺️ The First Global Empires</h3>
<p>Maritime empires focused on coastal bases, trade, and plantations rather than vast interior conquest. Each European state built its empire differently, based on geography and economic strategy.</p>
<h4>Portuguese Empire — <em>Estado da Índia</em></h4>
<ul>
<li>A chain of coastal forts and trading posts from Mozambique to Macau, plus Brazil.</li>
<li><strong>Goa</strong> (1510): Portuguese capital in India.</li>
<li><strong>Malacca</strong> (1511): Strategic chokepoint between the Indian Ocean and South China Sea.</li>
<li><strong>Hormuz</strong> (1515) and <strong>Macau</strong> (1557): Key bases.</li>
<li><strong>Cartaz system:</strong> Ships paying a fee to Portuguese authorities received a license; ships without one were seized. Not an empire of land, but a "protection racket" on the seas.</li>
<li><strong>Brazil</strong> became Portugal's great plantation colony, based on sugar and, by 1700, gold.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Spanish Empire</h4>
<ul>
<li>Large <strong>land-based</strong> empire in the Americas centered on Mexico City and Lima, built atop the conquered Aztec and Inca states.</li>
<li><strong>Encomienda</strong> and later <strong>hacienda</strong> systems organized Native labor on Spanish estates.</li>
<li><strong>Silver mining</strong> at <strong>Potosí</strong> (Bolivia, from 1545) and <strong>Zacatecas</strong> (Mexico) poured silver into the global economy.</li>
<li><strong>Manila</strong> (founded 1571) linked Spanish America to Ming/Qing China through the Manila Galleon.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Potosi.jpg?width=800" alt="Potosí, Bolivia" />
<figcaption>Potosí, Bolivia — site of the richest silver mine in the world. At its peak the city had a population of ~160,000, rivalling London, and its silver fueled global trade through Spanish and Manila Galleon fleets.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Dutch Empire</h4>
<ul>
<li>Built largely by the <strong>VOC (Dutch East India Company, 1602)</strong>, the world's first multinational joint-stock company.</li>
<li>Dominated the spice trade in the <strong>Indonesian archipelago</strong>, forcing monopolies on nutmeg (Banda Islands) and cloves.</li>
<li>Colonies at the Cape of Good Hope (1652), New Amsterdam (1624–1664), and Batavia (Jakarta).</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/VOC_Amsterdam.jpg?width=700" alt="VOC ship Amsterdam" />
<figcaption>A replica of the VOC ship <em>Amsterdam</em>. Dutch VOC ships carried spices from the Indonesian archipelago to European markets and made Amsterdam the financial capital of the 17th century.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>English Empire</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>British East India Company (EIC, 1600):</strong> Focused on cotton textiles from India.</li>
<li><strong>Jamestown</strong> (1607), Massachusetts Bay (1620–1630), Caribbean sugar colonies (Barbados by 1627, Jamaica 1655).</li>
<li>Increasingly took over Dutch and French commercial positions during the 17th–18th centuries.</li>
</ul>
<h4>French Empire</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>New France</strong> (Quebec 1608, Montreal 1642): Fur-trading empire reliant on alliances with Native peoples.</li>
<li>Caribbean sugar colonies: <strong>Saint-Domingue</strong> (Haiti) became the wealthiest colony in the world by the 18th century.</li>
<li>Trading posts in India (Pondicherry) and the Mississippi Valley (Louisiana, 1682).</li>
</ul>
<h4>The Atlantic Slave Trade</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Triangular trade:</strong> European manufactured goods → Africa; enslaved Africans → Americas (the Middle Passage); American plantation products (sugar, tobacco, later cotton) → Europe.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Triangular_trade.png?width=700" alt="Triangular trade diagram" />
<figcaption>The triangular trade: a simplified model of the three-cornered Atlantic system connecting Europe, Africa, and the Americas.</figcaption>
</figure>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Slave_ship_diagram.png?width=700" alt="Slave ship stowage plan" />
<figcaption>Stowage plan of the British slave ship <em>Brookes</em> (1788). Published by abolitionists, this diagram illustrates the brutal conditions of the Middle Passage, in which an estimated 12.5 million Africans were forcibly transported, about 2 million of whom died en route.</figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.5 -->
<h2>Topic 4.5 — Maritime Empires Maintained and Developed</h2>
<div class="region-card region-mercantile">
<h3>💰 Mercantilism, Joint-Stock Companies, and the Silver Trade</h3>
<p>
Controlling an empire required new financial and political institutions. The 16th–18th centuries saw
the rise of <strong>mercantilism</strong>, joint-stock companies, and a truly global silver-based
economy.
</p>
<h4>Mercantilism</h4>
<ul>
<li>Economic theory that the world's wealth was fixed and measured in bullion (gold and silver).</li>
<li>Governments promoted <strong>exports</strong>, restricted <strong>imports</strong>, and kept colonial trade in their own merchants' hands.</li>
<li>Examples: English <strong>Navigation Acts</strong> (from 1651), French <strong>Colbertism</strong>, Spanish monopoly on trade with its American colonies (Seville, later Cádiz).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Joint-Stock Companies</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>English EIC (1600)</strong> and <strong>Dutch VOC (1602)</strong>: Investors bought shares to pool capital and spread risk. These companies had quasi-state powers — their own armies, coinage, and ability to wage war.</li>
<li>Eventually the VOC employed more soldiers than most European states and ruled territory in Asia.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/East_India_House_THS_1817_edited.jpg?width=700" alt="East India House, London" />
<figcaption>East India House, London — headquarters of the English East India Company. Companies like the EIC and VOC combined private investment with state-backed violence.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Silver and the Global Economy</h4>
<ul>
<li>Spanish silver from Potosí and Zacatecas flowed across the Atlantic to Europe and across the Pacific on the <strong>Manila Galleon</strong>.</li>
<li>Ming (and later Qing) China demanded silver as payment after switching to a <strong>"single-whip" tax system</strong> that required silver payment; this created huge Chinese demand that kept the global silver trade running.</li>
<li>Silver flowing into Europe caused the <strong>price revolution</strong> — long-term inflation that disrupted feudal incomes and benefited merchants.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Commercial Revolution in Europe</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Banking houses</strong> (Fugger, Medici), stock exchanges (Amsterdam 1602, London 1698), insurance (Lloyd's of London).</li>
<li><strong>New forms of credit</strong>: futures, shares, bonds.</li>
<li>Rise of a <strong>merchant middle class</strong> (bourgeoisie) whose wealth increasingly rivalled that of landed nobles.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Labor Systems</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Encomienda &amp; repartimiento</strong> (Spanish Americas): forced Native labor.</li>
<li><strong>Mit'a</strong> (repurposed Inca labor tax): used in Potosí silver mines.</li>
<li><strong>Chattel slavery</strong> of Africans in plantation colonies: the dominant form of bound labor in the Atlantic world by the 17th c.</li>
<li><strong>Indentured servitude</strong>: Europeans (and later Asians) contracted to labor for a set term in exchange for passage.</li>
<li><strong>Serfdom</strong> expanded in Russia and Eastern Europe even as it declined in the West — "second serfdom."</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.6 -->
<h2>Topic 4.6 — Internal and External Challenges to State Power</h2>
<div class="region-card region-resist">
<h3>✊ Revolts, Rebellions, and Limits of Empire</h3>
<p>
No empire's rule went unchallenged. Europeans, enslaved Africans, indigenous peoples, and subject
classes pushed back against imperial and state power in different ways.
</p>
<h4>European Challenges to Absolutism</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Fronde (France, 1648–1653):</strong> Noble and popular revolts against royal centralization; ultimately helped Louis XIV consolidate power.</li>
<li><strong>Glorious Revolution (England, 1688):</strong> Parliament invited William and Mary to replace James II; English Bill of Rights (1689) established parliamentary supremacy and limited monarchy.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Resistance in the Americas</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pueblo Revolt (1680):</strong> Led by Popé; Pueblo peoples in present-day New Mexico expelled the Spanish for 12 years after decades of forced Catholic conversions and labor demands.</li>
<li><strong>Metacom's War (King Philip's War, 1675–1676):</strong> Wampanoag, Nipmuc, and allied peoples fought against English expansion in New England.</li>
<li><strong>Maroon societies:</strong> Escaped enslaved Africans built independent communities in Jamaica, Suriname (Saramaka), Brazil (<strong>Quilombo dos Palmares</strong>, which at its height held 20,000 people).</li>
<li><strong>Stono Rebellion (1739):</strong> Enslaved Africans in South Carolina marched toward Spanish Florida; suppressed but influenced later slave codes.</li>
<li><strong>Túpac Amaru II (1780)</strong> in Peru — at the tail end of the period — led a major uprising of Native peoples and mestizos against Spanish rule.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Resistance by Enslaved Africans</h4>
<ul>
<li>On ships: mutinies on the Middle Passage.</li>
<li>On plantations: sabotage, escape, feigned illness, religious syncretism (Vodou in Haiti, Candomblé in Brazil, Santería in Cuba).</li>
<li>Major revolts: the precursor to Unit 5's Haitian Revolution (1791–1804), but rooted in the resistance traditions of this period.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Asian Powers Push Back</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Tokugawa Japan</strong>: Expelled Portuguese missionaries and largely closed the country (<em>sakoku</em>, from the 1630s), keeping only limited Dutch and Chinese trade at Nagasaki.</li>
<li><strong>Ming/Qing China</strong>: Restricted European trade to Canton under the <strong>Canton system</strong>; Chinese officials remained the gatekeepers of foreign trade until 1842.</li>
<li><strong>Ottomans, Mughals, and Safavids</strong>: Still far stronger than European powers on land; European expansion into these regions was still limited before 1750.</li>
</ul>
<h4>State Responses</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Slave codes</strong> (e.g., the French <em>Code Noir</em>, 1685; English and Spanish versions) aimed to regulate the growing enslaved population.</li>
<li><strong>Missionary efforts</strong> (Jesuits, Franciscans, Dominicans) were both agents of empire and, occasionally, critics of it (e.g., Bartolomé de Las Casas defended Indigenous peoples).</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.7 -->
<h2>Topic 4.7 — Changing Social Hierarchies</h2>
<div class="region-card region-social">
<h3>👥 Race, Class, and New Social Orders</h3>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Casta_painting_all.jpg?width=800" alt="Casta painting from colonial Mexico" />
<figcaption>An 18th-century <strong>casta painting</strong> from New Spain, illustrating the colonial racial hierarchy. Each panel shows a mixed-race family and labels their socially defined category.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Colonial Latin America — The <em>Casta</em> System</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Peninsulares:</strong> Spaniards born in Spain; held the highest offices.</li>
<li><strong>Creoles (<em>criollos</em>):</strong> People of European descent born in the Americas; wealthy but barred from top posts.</li>
<li><strong>Mestizos:</strong> European-Indigenous mixed ancestry.</li>
<li><strong>Mulattoes:</strong> European-African mixed ancestry.</li>
<li><strong>Indigenous peoples and enslaved Africans</strong> held the lowest status.</li>
<li>The casta system attempted to define dozens of racial categories, reflecting anxiety about mixing in an increasingly mestizo society.</li>
</ul>
<h4>North America</h4>
<ul>
<li>Racial slavery became increasingly entrenched and race-based: by the late 1600s, English colonies like Virginia codified that Africans and their descendants were enslaved for life and that slave status passed through the mother.</li>
<li>Rise of a small but important free Black community, especially in the Chesapeake and Louisiana.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Europe</h4>
<ul>
<li>Rise of the <strong>bourgeoisie</strong> (urban merchant and professional classes) challenged the social dominance of the old landed nobility.</li>
<li>The Dutch Republic — dominated by urban merchants — was the template for a commercial society.</li>
<li>Status increasingly tied to <strong>wealth</strong>, not just birth — but aristocracy remained politically dominant.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Africa</h4>
<ul>
<li>Slave-raiding warfare reshaped political structures. <strong>Oyo</strong>, <strong>Asante</strong>, <strong>Benin</strong>, and <strong>Dahomey</strong> expanded in part by acquiring firearms in exchange for enslaved people.</li>
<li>Gender imbalances in West and Central Africa as mostly male captives were sent across the Atlantic reshaped family structures.</li>
<li>The <strong>Kingdom of Kongo</strong> converted to Catholicism (first contact 1483) but was weakened by the slave trade.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Asia</h4>
<ul>
<li>Chinese and Indian merchant networks remained strong. Europeans operated inside existing systems — e.g., trading at Canton — rather than replacing them.</li>
<li>Opium and cotton textiles began to reshape the Asian–European–American trade triangle in ways that would become dramatic in Unit 5.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 4.8 -->
<h2>Topic 4.8 — Continuity and Change: 1450–1750</h2>
<div class="region-card region-compare">
<h3>🔄 What Changed — and What Stayed the Same?</h3>
<h4>Major Changes</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Global economy:</strong> For the first time, the Americas, Africa, Europe, and Asia were tied into a single trading system.</li>
<li><strong>Demographic revolution:</strong> Native American populations collapsed; European and African populations in the Americas grew; new biological exchanges transformed diets and populations worldwide.</li>
<li><strong>Rise of Atlantic economies:</strong> Sugar, tobacco, and silver made the Atlantic the most dynamic economic zone in the world by 1750.</li>
<li><strong>Race-based slavery:</strong> Though slavery was old, the Atlantic system created an unprecedented system of <strong>chattel slavery based on race</strong>.</li>
<li><strong>New financial institutions:</strong> Joint-stock companies, stock exchanges, and public debt transformed European economies.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Continuities</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Agriculture</strong> remained the basis of most economies — most people still farmed.</li>
<li><strong>Patriarchal societies</strong> dominated worldwide.</li>
<li><strong>Religion</strong> still legitimized rulers and ordered daily life.</li>
<li><strong>Land-based empires</strong> (Ottoman, Safavid, Mughal, Qing, Russian) remained powerful — Europeans did not yet dominate Asia.</li>
<li>Asian economies — particularly Indian textiles and Chinese manufacturing — were still larger and more productive than Europe's.</li>
</ul>
